%N A395267 Decimal expansion of 1/3 + 3*sqrt(3)/(4*Pi).
%C A395267 The probability that a chord determined by two points independently and uniformly selected at random in a disk is longer than a side of an equilateral triangle inscribed in the disk (Garwood and Holroyd, 1966).
%C A395267 Bertrand (1889) gave three possible definitions for a random chord, for which the corresponding probabilities are 1/3, 1/2, or 1/4.
%C A395267 Note that the probability calculated by Garwood and Holroyd (1966) is that the chord's distance from the center of the circle is larger than sqrt(3). It equals 1 minus this constant, i.e., 2/3 - 3*sqrt(3)/(4*Pi) = 0.253169... .
%D A395267 Gábor J. Székely, Paradoxes in Probability Theory and Mathematical Statistics, Reidel, 1986, p. 47.
%H A395267 Vangalur S. Alagar and Larry H. Thiel, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1109/TPAMI.1981.4767097">Algorithms for detecting M-dimensional objects in N-dimensional spaces</a>, IEEE Transactions on Pattern Analysis and Machine Intelligence, Vol PAMI-3, No. 3 (1981), pp. 245-256.
%H A395267 Joseph Bertrand, <a href="https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k99602b/f65.item">Calcul des probabilités</a>, Gauthier-Villars, Paris, 1889, pp. 5-6.
%H A395267 F. Garwood and E. M. Holroyd, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/3614676">The Distance of a "Random Chord" of a Circle from the Centre</a>, The Mathematical Gazette, Vol. 50, No. 373 (1966), pp. 283-286.
%H A395267 P. A. P. Moran, <a href="https://doi.org/10.2307/1426409">A second note on recent research in geometrical probability</a>, Advances in Applied Probability , Vol. 1, No. 1 (1969) , pp. 73-89.
%H A395267 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/BertrandsProblem.html">Bertrand's Problem</a>.
%H A395267 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bertrand_paradox_(probability)">Bertrand paradox (probability)</a>.
%H A395267 <a href="/index/Tra#transcendental">Index entries for transcendental numbers</a>.
